  <p>Inheriting a house in Wichita can feel like a gift and a burden at the same time. You're grieving, sorting through a lifetime of belongings, and now there's a property to deal with. The last thing you need is a six-month listing process with a Realtor asking you to paint the walls and replace the carpet.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>💡 <strong>The short version:</strong> You have three main options — list with a Realtor, sell it yourself, or sell to a cash buyer. Each has real trade-offs. This article breaks them down honestly.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Do You Have to Go Through Probate?</h2>
  <p>In most cases in Kansas, yes. If the deceased didn't set up a trust or transfer-on-death deed, the property needs to go through Sedgwick County probate court before it can be sold. A straightforward estate typically moves through in 4–6 months.</p>
  <p><strong>Important:</strong> you can have a purchase agreement in place before probate closes. A cash buyer can work on your timeline and wait for probate to finalize — so you're not rushing when it does.</p>

  <h2>Your Three Main Options</h2>

  <h3>1. List With a Realtor</h3>
  <p>If the house is in good shape and you're not in a hurry, this can get you the highest price. But factor in: 5–6% agent commission, repair costs to get it market-ready, carrying costs (taxes, insurance, utilities) during the listing period, and the real possibility of deals falling through.</p>

  <h3>2. Sell It Yourself (FSBO)</h3>
  <p>Saves the commission but requires a lot of work — especially with the title complications that often come with inherited properties. You'll still need a real estate attorney and a title company. Works best for experienced sellers with a move-in-ready home.</p>

  <h3>3. Sell to a Cash Home Buyer</h3>
  <p>No repairs. No cleaning. No showings. Get an offer in 24 hours and close when probate clears — or as fast as 7 days after. The offer will typically be below full retail market value, but when you subtract commissions, repairs, and months of carrying costs, the difference is often smaller than you'd think.</p>

  <h2>Common Situations We See With Inherited Properties</h2>
  <ul>
